–Overleden","1339–Male":"1339–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1356–Male":"1356–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1455":"1455","1356":"1356","about 1339":"circa 1339","about 1356":"circa 1356","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Shadingfield, Suffolk, England":"Shadingfield, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1339–":"about 1339–Deceased","1339–Male":"1339–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1356–Male":"1356–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1455":"1455","1356":"1356","about 1339":"about 1339","about 1356":"about 1356","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Shadingfield, Suffolk, England":"Shadingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Duke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>duk(ke)</i>, <i>duck</i>, <i>doke</i>, <i>dook</i> ‘duck’ (Old English <i>dūce</i>), either from a perceived resemblance (perhaps a waddling gait) or from association with wild fowling. Compare   Duck  ,   Drake  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Duk</i> or <i>Duke</i>. In northern England this is usually a pet form of <i>Marmaduke</i>. It may alternatively be a survival of one or more Old English personal names, though it is uncertain whether they were still current in the period of surname formation. Old English <i>Ducc(a)</i> is attested in placenames like Duxford (Cambridgeshire) and Duckington (Cheshire), and was perhaps interchangeable with <i>Docc</i>, attested in Doxey (Staffordshire) and Doxford (Northumberland). <i>Duke</i> could also represent Old English <i>Deowuc</i> (as in Deuxhill, Shropshire). A surname from <i>Marmaduke</i> is on record until at least 1881 and derives from the personal name <i>Marmaduke</i>, apparently an Anglo-Norman French pronunciation of Old Irish <i>Maolmaedóc</i> ‘devotee of <i>Maedóc</i>’; see   Duckett  .","Americanized form of Polish <b>Duk</b>: nickname from <i>dukać</i> ‘to stammer or falter’."],"variants":[{"name":"Dock","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Duke  .","Norwegian: habitational name from a farm named Dokk, from Old Norse <i>dǫkk</i> ‘hollow, depression’.","North German (Lower Saxony): possibly a metonymic occupational name for someone who worked in the cloth trade, from Middle Low German <i>dōk</i> ‘fabric’."]},{"name":"Doke","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  ."]},{"name":"Duch","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Nga, Phal, Phan, Sophan, Tha, Thang, Yen.  German Kurt, Klaus.","Polish, Sorbian, and Ukrainian: nickname from <i>duch</i> ‘spirit, breath’.","Czech: from a short form of the Old Czech personal name <i>Duchoslav</i>, composed of the elements <i>duch</i> ‘spirit’ + <i>slav</i> ‘glory’ or ‘famous’."]},{"name":"Duckett","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Duket</i>. This may sometimes have been an early Middle English pet form of an Old English <i>Ducc(a)</i>, but was more often a pet form of <i>Marmaduke</i>, especially in Yorkshire (see   Duke  ). <i>Marmaduke</i> itself is from Irish <i>Maol Maedóc</i> ‘servant of Maedóc’, <i>Maedóc</i> being the name of prominent Irish saints of the 6th and 7th centuries."]},{"name":"Duck","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  .","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as an equivalent of <b>Lohan</b> (an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Leocháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Leochán</i>’) by mistranslation, as if from <i>lacha</i> ‘duck’.","North German (also <b>Dück</b>) and German (<b>Dück</b>): see   Dueck  ."]},{"name":"Dukes","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":43,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":116,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Walter Duke was born about 1339 as the son of Unknown Duke. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Duke. He died in England."},"et":{"about 1339–":"umbes 1339–Surnud","1339–Male":"1339–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1356–Male":"1356–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1455":"1455","1356":"1356","about 1339":"umbes 1339","about 1356":"umbes 1356","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Shadingfield, Suffolk, England":"Shadingfield, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1339–":"noin 1339–Kuollut","1339–Male":"1339–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1